you can add healing frequency music in the background yourself (in another tab on lower volume) and it offers a really nice meditative space, especially for slower paced videos. 

‚òÖ 396 Hertz: DO. It is usually related to guilt and fear, and how they can suppress other emotions as well. It is associated with the color red.

‚òÖ 417 Hertz: RE. It is usually related to past trauma and negativity and the willingness to change. This frequency can help you to recognize those past traumas that are no longer valuable in your life. It is associated with the color orange.

‚òÖ 528 Hertz: MI. It is usually related to DNA, peace of mind and clarity. This frequency will help you heal and remove any sickness you may have. It is associated with the color yellow.

‚òÖ 639 Hertz: FA. It is usually related to Interpersonal relationships. This frequency will help you heal those difficult relationships you still have from the past while also reconnecting with those who are valuable in your present. It is associated with the color green.

‚òÖ 741 Hertz: SOL. It is usually related to the emotional stability you are looking for. This frequency will help you solve any problems you may have in your life. It is associated with the color blue.

‚òÖ 852 Hertz: LA. It is usually related to the views of oneself and the universe. It requires open space in order to allow intuition to come in. It is associated with the color indigo.

‚òÖ 963 Hertz: SI. it is usually related to the feeling of oneness. It means awakening and interconnected to the universe. This frequency helps you to reconnect with yourself. It is associated with the color purple.

November 1, 2020
Starting Dedicate. 
Something brought me here is right. This burning need to reassert myself and start taking better care of me. I am a fierce, strong woman with a shit ton on my plate right now. I'm a sporadic yogi at the moment but with hopes to get back on the train. Adrienne is where I began my journey years ago and she will be the one to bring me back. Here's the thing though. My impatience is something I need to work on. I almost quit this video half way through because of the pace but instead I took our lovely leaders advice and made this practice my own. I moved when I felt the need to move. My mountain had a soft sway today with just a touch of boogie woogie, down dog went to plank and back a few times. I moved with my breath and intention. That is what is so great about a home practice. It can look however you NEED it to look that day! So much love and thanks from the bottom of my heart! I felt the worst shake when I pulled my elbows in during halfway lift. Now there's some muscles that don't get much attention!

Starting Dedicate after joining YWA community to do Home in May. I've been inspired by the sharing in the comments and the building of community there, so I wanted to share myself. Today is my 32nd birthday and although I am safe and well, I am feeling for the many injustices of the world right now, leaving me more sorrowful this birthday. It is okay to feel sorrow on my birthday. For Home I focused on reconnecting with my physical body after feeling that I had mainly used it as a vehicle for at least the last decade rather than upholding it as the beautiful instrument that it is. For Dedicate I am intending to love myself. This is partially in response to struggling to find lasting, connected, loving friendships in adulthood. It seems that I am not able to womanifest such friendships, so maybe I need to take that bounding love and desire I have been trying to share with others and direct it inward. Thank you for holding me accountable everyone, as I know that you will. Sending you love, light, and warmth, and hoping you each feel the freedom to love yourself. In a society that often activates us into fear to weaken our collective power and profiteers off of our doubt, loving oneself feels like a radical act that will bring healing. All my birthday wishes are for peace.

Adriene, I've been tense since I was born. As a baby, I was kind of rigid and didn't melt into my mother's arms, as a kid I remember being frustrated that my legs felt like they wouldn't fully relax when I lay down for bed, and as a young adult I sit very rigidly, walk tightly, always feel like muscles are tightened, and feel restricted in my movement.

During this yoga practice I heard and felt thing creaking, cracking, and popping and it felt amazing! I knew it was the feeling of my body trying to finally start to loosen a little. I felt all my blood flowing like crazy and felt my mind connect to my body.

I've always had problems with yoga feeling like it can be boring and painful. The way you connect mind to body and your sense of humor mean I'm not bored for a second and your practices don't feel painful either, even when they're challenging! Thank you for every video you put out. I'm extremely excited for this series!

Thank you. I've come here after 74 months of fighting a chronic illness, and it's meant I've barely been able to exercise at all in those six years for fear of making the prognosis worse.  I always meant to try Yoga in that time, but trying to get to a class was both intimidating with how limited I was (I used to be really active) and I could never know if I would be well enough on a set day per week.

10 days ago I hit the highest point of frustration, anger, everything at everything. I'm 31, now just barely too old to qualify for a lot of the youth opportunities I wanted to try but wasn't able to. But, something changed when I hit that low. For the last week I've been filled with energy, and while I'm burning it up making plans and getting things done in my life again, I also found my way here.

I don't know now what the outcome will be. It's possible tomorrow or next week I will slide right back down to where I was and I won't be able to do all 30 days. It's possible I'll just keep feeling better and in a month I can take the steps to get back to normal life. Either way, while I have the energy and the strength I am going to give this everything I have. Whatever the outcome, I'll post again when I get there. So let's hope you don't hear from me for 30 days haha.

I'm a couple months late, but I'm here. For the last 3 years I've suffered from a variety of injuries, one in particular that happened last year that really hit me hard. I was umpiring Men's A Grade softball, with the pitcher pitching at approximately 110 km/hr. Unfortunately, the ball managed to hit where there is no padding for a plate umpire - the hip. I spent 2 months bed bound (a 2 inch crack on my hip bone) and 8 months of physio and rehab following. But it didn't feel like it was enough, until my Mum found this journey and told me to give it a go - she thinks maybe a slower, more intimate approach to rehab may be the best way to get me back to my full potential so I can play my beloved sports (field hockey and softball) again this year.

Adriene, I know you get flooded with sweet comments and there is a reason for it. I'm here to write you another one. I really don't know how you do it but somehow, every time, you crack my chest open. It took me a while to come back to my mat but today I decided to show up for myself once again. I'll admit I was hesitant when I saw how long the video was. I stepped on my mat thinking I didn't have enough time and even though I love hearing your voice, I kept fidgeting during the beginning. But I stuck with it (because I am worth it) and after fighting against my body for about half the video I decided to just let it go. I stopped comparing how weak my body felt now to how I used to feel before I took a hiatus. I have to tell you I don't think I would've gotten to that point without your sweet sweet words. Every time I felt guilt or shame or anger at my body, you were there with an encouraging word or kind statement to help me through and shift my perspective. The tears came during mountain pose when I finally felt myself surrendering and they continued throughout the rest of the practice. I just wanted to say thank you, from the deepest depths of my heart Adriene, for all that you do and for sharing your kindness with the world. I am so excited to get back on my mat tomorrow and to start matching my actions with my intentions.

I'm a 43 year old guy who was told by his doctor that I either lowered my stress levels, or I would be dead. She suggested yoga. As my main interests in life are heavy metal and causing mayhem, I thought she was crazy. However, I didn't want to be dead so I signed up for classes and it blew me away. I learned that yoga is about a lot more than stretching. I also made friends with everyone and they all saw past my leather jacket and black jeans to who I really was. I eventually moved from the east coast to San Diego and signed up for yoga here. Unfortunately, my job started late, so I had to wait to sign up full-time. After a hard day, I was on the interwebs looking for something online to take the edge off, and I found this.
What a find.
You are honest, open-minded, and funny as heck. Between saying things like "jibber-jabber," "I'll kick your butt later,"  "PHSSHEEEW," "Bells and whistles like Bugs Bunny," "That's the title of my fourth book," and actually singing a little at one point, I found the main message here to be "You are NOT alone." At one point I went back to the beginning and put this on surround sound and turned the TV off.
So I know this was just the beginning, but I have a feeling that this is going someplace good. It's nice to have so much commentary because it helps me really think about doing things well and comfortably (and get out of me head). Thank you for putting so much work into this. This middle-aged metal-head is excited to be a part of this. I can tell you're special, and so are these videos. See you in 30 says :)

Hi Adriene,
I just finished this and I am feeling grateful. Discern: to perceive or recognize something. I feel I am recognizing myself. This practice indeed, brought me back to my love~cave within. Recently I started reading a book called, "The Courage to be Disliked" -- it touches on Alderian Psychology. It has taught me so much, introducing me to a new subjective way of interacting with this physical world. I am recognizing myself more and more, and feel compelled to take care of my self, my growth, my time, and my physical body. This is why I am doing this practice today. Perhaps, that's interesting for you to read. The background and personal story of this individual perspective as to why I am compelled towards this lovely practice that you've provided. You are connected to my journey and my seemingly cosmic self shift and I am extremely grateful for the practice you yourself have dedicated yourself to. Namaste.

Adriene, Thank you, thank you, thank you! I hope you have no doubts that your relentless gift-giving is giving me the tools to change my life! For years I have lived in a tense state, unconscious to my breath, and to the layers of stress and pain that I have carried in my feet, hips, and shoulders, ever since I over-committed to the whole warrior ethos of contact sport (rugby) as a wee lad (and crucially, I did so without proper conditioning, physical or mental). In recent years, I have realised I am a man of peace, and that I really want to spend my time traipsing around the beautiful American West backcountry in a kind of euphoric walking meditation. This goal has been hindered by my feet - specifically, the fact that I have for most of my life only been using half of them, walking mostly on the inside edges, while the outer edges have withered for lack of use like a tyrannousaurus rex's arms, obsolete and numb.

I signed up to your emails in December 2016, and then spent a year for some reason not doing your videos. I think I was scared - I've known for years that yoga would be good for me, but it always seemed so hard! I was used to seeing myself as strong and athletic, and I did NOT feel that way doing yoga. I felt incredibly tight, and just incompetent. But in January 2017, I started to try, and I began to learn to listen to my body, to identify where i was holding tension, and to explore new movements slowly and while observing what effects arise in all the different parts of my body. In September 2017, I committed myself to daily practice with your videos, starting with the TRUE journey. I have occasionally read the message boards and noticed that everyone's positive comments had a buoying effect on me; making me more confident and determined, and even fooling me into thinking I'm not just doing this alone in my girlfriend's mum's living room while her dogs stare at me, all quizzical and bemused at this lone yogic nutter. 

TLDR: This video is a beauty! So good to go slow and learn some new things about moves I rarely take the time to think deeply about now. In particular, I had an epiphany about moving between downward dog and forward fold - who knew how much sensation you can experience in the feet during this transition! Rolling deliberately through my feet helped me feel rooted, while also stretching more deeply through my back. Surprisingly for me, this video was not easy, physically, even though I have been gaining strength and control practicing Adriene's core workouts for a while now. It took work to strengthen my breath control, and to move through the poses while keeping my shoulders loose and relaxed.

At the end, I felt so light and loose, and deeply present in my movements. I almost didn't want to get up. Does anyone have any wisdom to share about how to maintain that mindfulness and ease as you move through your day? How many people who practice daily in the morning also practice in the afternoon or evening? If so, what does your second practice look like?
This practice made me laugh and let my cry. It reminded me that it is okay to feel. Thank you Adrieneüíô

I paused the video around 43:00 because I had inspiration to write, and wanted to share what I discovered: 
"How slowly can you take 2019? We are constantly told 'Carpe Diem' or 'Seize the Day,' but I feel that puts a lot of pressure on you to go out and do EVERYTHING in that moment, as if you have no time. What if you woke up each day and just took it at the pace you wanted to? With your breath, taking everything as it comes and feeling the space to be creative rather than panicking about what you're not doing or accomplishing? 
This year I choose to not feel guilty for going my speed. I choose to enjoy where I am and always remember that the choices I make have ripple effects that I won't even think about, to make them really count toward what I believe in. Spread the love, spread the steady and the stable, the logical, the honest, the genuine. 
You are your actions."

I discerned that I need to let go more. Don't whine to myself, don't wiggle around in the poses nervously, just let go and let my muscles and bones work together and breathe. Thank you so much!

I started doing Yoga with you 2 years ago now, but this is my first time following the 30 days of Yoga live, and I'm so happy to do this. This year is a pretty special one for me, it's already my fourth month living abroad and only now I'm starting to get back to have a routine, to get back what was part of me and in between those things there is Yoga too. 
From the exact time I came to China I felt like there was no time to dedicate to myself, no space since I live in a little room with another person, no will to give myself a pause. But then I realized that rushing that much not to lose the time here, I was loosing me, my body, and my mind. And this is not right, you can not build anything if you don't have a strong base that keep you up. And so today I choose, I choose to get back to the origins, to me and to find what it feels good, because one hour is not that much, because even in a 5 meters of room you can find space if you want. So thank you as always Adriene, for being here, for what you do. Because even when I am 8000 kilometers away from "home", I can feel like home doing yoga, cause the real home is just when my mind is at ease and I am one with my body and mind. 
Namaste <3

Every few months, I come back to this channel and tell myself I'm going to complete a 30 day challenge - one of my goals for 2018 was to be able to do the crow pose properly and for longer than a few seconds of wobbling! Didn't happen! But 2018 was a hard year with lots of trials and very few tribulations, and this year I'm determined to start it off right! My partner recently had a not terrible injury, but it's to his hand, and it's completely changed the way we've both had to view the world and our capabilities - you don't realise what you've got until it's gone, and he's lost a lot of his fitness-based activities because of the pain and immobility in that hand now. So I feel like I owe it to him, as well as myself, to actually act on the never ending "I'm gonna do it, I'm gonna get fit, I'm gonna do this that and the other" and actually achieve it. And I think, with the endless smiles I find my face covered with whenever I watch and engage with one of Adriene's videos, I'm going to make it happen. Let 2019  commence! x

Hello friends from all over the world. I am so honoured that I can go on this journey with all of you that are on a different stage of life. Let's keep doing this together. I have had such rough past few years financially, physically, and mentally, as I lost my goal, had to leave my job, had to leave the country I had lived for 8 years due to unavoidable situation, and also got a lot of physical disorders/symptoms that require several medications, so I started feeling hopeless and deeply depressed, stopped physical activities, stopped doing yoga, stopped searching for a job, just chose to be stuck in my room for days without interacting with anybody, however, I choose to rise again, this year, 2019, I choose to be hopeful, I choose to tend to myself, thank you for helping me get out of my own pit shining my dark path Adrienne!  Day 1 checked in! It feels so right and I feel so relieved and encouraged that there are lots of us walking on this yoga journey together!

Last year I needed to find equilibrium. I was in a very bad place and your yoga was the perfect pick me up. In the end I felt so much love from the community and so proud of myself for sticking with the practice even when it felt hard or impossible. This year I want to pay attention to my body and to really listen to it. As my practice continues to evolve I want to start understanding that this is a journey and that some days I feel weaker and my yoga might need a slight adjustment and that that is absolutely okay because in other days I might actually crave some fire. It's all about balance and harmony. 
I wish all of you taking part in this journey good luck! Don't forget to enjoy it, that's the most important part and do it for yourself, not for some expectation of outcome or anything like that. Dedicate it to yourself. Sending you all love. And thank you Adriene, for your kindness and for bringing us together, for another year of beautiful yoga üíõ
